  # AR-forge-architecture: Forge architecture
  
  This document describes the high-level implementation shape of Forge:
  which component owns each phase of the issue resolution defined in
  §FS-forge-issue-resolution-goal, where extensibility lives, and which
  boundaries keep generated work reviewable. The behavior Forge must satisfy is
  defined by §FS-forge-functional-spec; this file records the implementation
  structure chosen to satisfy it, with the workflow catalog in
  §FS-forge-workflow-spec-catalog as the behavior surface.
  
  ## Architecture Map
  
  | ID | Concern |
  | --- | --- |
  | §AR-forge-architecture | overview of Forge implementation boundaries |
  | §DW-do-work-loop | worker bootstrap, self-update, stop markers, and cycle scheduling |
  | §ORCH-forge-orchestration-spec | orchestration scripts: GitHub queue claiming, worktree setup, workflow dispatch, publication handoff, and issue/project bookkeeping |
  | §GIT-forge-publication | git-scripts publication: staging, commit, PR body, labels, and issue linking |
  | §WF-forge-workflow-system | behavioral contract for the workflow layer |
  | §WF-forge-workflow-architecture | implementation split for workflow drivers, strategy configuration, workflow engines, utilities, and publication handoff |
  | §WF-forge-workflow-drivers | behavioral contract for deterministic workflow drivers |
  | §STRAT-forge-predefined-strategy-contract | behavioral contract for named strategy configuration bundles |
  | §AR-forge-control-plane | how the worker loop, dispatcher, GitHub queues, and worktrees compose |
  | §AR-forge-workflow-boundary | how workflow drivers turn a claimed issue into an isolated workflow run |
  | §AR-forge-strategy-agent-boundary | how strategy configuration, workflow engines, agents, and post-generation interventions are separated |
  | §AR-forge-verification-publication-boundary | why PR creation is a publication step after verification, not part of generation |
  | §AR-forge-extension-points | where new issue queues, strategies, agents, and PR types plug in |
  | §STRAT-workflow-strategy-registry | strategy registry and predefined strategy wiring |
  | §WF-forge-workflow-engine | workflow engines as state-machine-like run executors |
  | §WF-forge-workflow-strategy-config | predefined strategy bundles as workflow run configuration |
  
  ## AR-forge-control-plane: Worker loop and dispatcher own queue control
  
  Forge is shaped as a small control plane around independent workflow entry
  scripts, serving §FS-forge-issue-resolution-goal. `do-work.sh` is the stable
  shell entrypoint. It forwards arguments to `do_up_to_date_work.sh`, which keeps
  the local Forge checkout up to date, honors stop files, applies worker limits,
  and invokes `forge_metadata.py` for one work cycle, as described in
  §DW-do-work-loop. The dispatcher owns GitHub queue scanning, issue claiming,
  worktree creation, workflow routing, review queues, project status updates, and
  cleanup; its behavior and implementation are specified in
  §ORCH-forge-orchestration-spec. PR publication is delegated to the
  git-scripts component (§GIT-forge-publication) after the dispatcher
  observes a PR-eligible status; the dispatched workflows themselves are defined
  separately, in §WF-forge-workflow-system and §WF-forge-workflow-architecture.
  
  The dispatcher routes issue work by issue labels, not by PR labels:
  
  | Issue label | Workflow driver | Successful PR label |
  | --- | --- | --- |
  | `library-new-request` | `ai_workflows/add_new_library_support.py` | `library-new-request` |
  | `library-update-request` | `ai_workflows/improve_library_coverage.py` | `library-update-request` |
  | `fails-javac-compile` | `ai_workflows/fix_javac_fail.py` | `fixes-javac-fail` |
  | `fails-java-run` | `ai_workflows/fix_java_run_fail.py` | `fixes-java-run-fail` |
  | `fails-native-image-run` | `ai_workflows/fix_ni_run.py` | `fixes-native-image-run-fail` |
  
  The control plane treats a claimed issue as exclusive work. Claiming,
  assignment checks, worktree creation, and final unassignment all belong in
  `forge_metadata.py` and the GitHub helper layer rather than in individual
  workflow engines. Workflow drivers should receive already-resolved
  coordinates, paths, and strategy names; they should not reimplement queue
  policy.
  
  ```mermaid
  flowchart LR
      Wrapper["do-work.sh"]
      Worker["do_up_to_date_work.sh"]
      Dispatcher["forge_metadata.py"]
      GitHub[("GitHub issues / PRs / project")]
      Worktree[("isolated reachability worktree")]
      Entry["workflow driver"]
      PR["git_scripts/make_pr_*.py"]
  
      Wrapper --> Worker --> Dispatcher
      Dispatcher -->|scan + claim label| GitHub
      Dispatcher -->|create| Worktree
      Dispatcher -->|invoke| Entry
      Entry -->|status + metrics| Dispatcher
      Dispatcher -->|PR-eligible status| PR
      PR --> GitHub
      Dispatcher -->|failure / review bookkeeping| GitHub
  ```
  
  ## AR-forge-workflow-boundary: Workflow drivers compose setup, workflow engine, and metrics
  
  Workflow drivers are single-run boundaries, as defined by
  §WF-forge-workflow-drivers. They translate a claimed issue into one isolated
  run by resolving repository
  paths, pinning the GraalVM environment, creating or checking out the feature
  branch, preparing source context and required directories, loading the named
  predefined strategy, running the selected workflow engine, finalizing metadata,
  and writing schema-validated metrics.
  
  The workflow driver owns run setup and finalization; the workflow engine owns
  the state-machine-like issue-resolution process described in
  §WF-forge-workflow-architecture. The predefined strategy supplies configuration:
  which workflow engine, agent backend, model, prompt set, and workflow
  parameters are used for the run. This keeps every workflow aligned with the
  same repository, metrics, and local verification contracts
  (§FS-local-ci-equivalent-verification) while letting operators select different
  service profiles through configuration.
  
  The reachability repository must be present as a complete checkout or worktree
  for every generated artifact. Forge does not run Gradle-backed testing,
  dynamic-access reporting, metadata generation, or native tracing inside copied
  per-library fragments. That architecture keeps generated tests, metadata,
  Gradle build logic, stats, and Forge logs in one filesystem context.
  
  ## AR-forge-strategy-agent-boundary: Strategies configure workflows, agents edit code
  
  Registered workflow implementations own the generation loop. The codebase
  currently names their base class `WorkflowStrategy`, but architecturally those
  classes are workflow engines: they decide which prompt to send next, which
  Gradle command to run, how to interpret output, when to reset to a checkpoint,
  and which terminal status to return. Agents own only the editing and
  command-execution interface exposed by `Agent`: prompts, context management,
  token accounting, and test-command execution.
  
  This boundary lets a predefined strategy bind a workflow engine, agent, model,
  prompt-template set, workflow parameters, MCPs, and optional persistent
  instructions without changing the workflow driver or the workflow implementation.
  The workflow driver loads that bundle from `strategies/predefined_strategies.json`;
  it does not hard-code model-specific behavior.
  
  Post-generation recovery is built into the workflow base class, not a pluggable
  registry and not selected per strategy. When the post-iteration `./gradlew test`
  still fails during finalization, the base class runs a fixed Codex-then-Pi lane:
  a Codex metadata fix first, then Pi removing the offending failing tests as a
  last resort (see the post-generation intervention glossary in
  §FS-forge-functional-spec).
  
  Dynamic-access and native-test behavior stay in workflow specs, not in this
  architecture file. The architecture only fixes the boundaries: workflow engines
  call shared utilities for dynamic-access reports, and native test verification
  is a reusable gate (§WF-native-test-verification-gate) that drives native
  tracing and Codex recovery through the Gradle task contract in
  §WF-native-trace-gradle-tasks. The concrete agent API and Pi adapter are
  documented in §AR-agent-api, and the
  strategy bundles that bind these pieces live in the strategy registry
  (§STRAT-forge-predefined-strategy-contract, §STRAT-workflow-strategy-registry).
  
  ## AR-forge-verification-publication-boundary: Git scripts publish verified work
  
  Forge separates generation from publication. A workflow may edit tests,
  metadata, index files, stats, metrics, and logs while it runs, but PR creation
  is delegated to `git_scripts/make_pr_*.py` only after the dispatcher observes a
  PR-eligible status, as required by §FS-local-ci-equivalent-verification and
  §GIT-forge-publication. The publication script
  stages the expected paths, writes a commit message with metrics context, opens
  the pull request, applies the workflow-specific PR label, and links the result
  back to the issue.
  
  This boundary is especially important for chunked dynamic-access work. A
  non-final chunk publishes a reviewable PR that references the issue and carries
  the exhaust-report state needed by the next run, as specified in
  §WF-dynamic-access-exhaust-report. The final chunk is the only one allowed to
  close the issue. The publication layer must preserve that issue linking
  contract instead of treating every successful chunk as a completed issue
  (§WF-chunked-dynamic-access-pr-linking).
  
  Shared repository edits are allowed only when local verification proves they
  are necessary, and they must be surfaced in metrics and PR text for maintainer
  review. Publication is therefore not a blind `git add .`; it is the point where
  workflow-specific expected paths, labels, metrics, and human-intervention flags
  become visible to reviewers.
  
  ## AR-forge-extension-points: New behavior plugs into one boundary at a time
  
  Forge extension points are intentionally narrow:
  
  - Add an issue queue by adding a label route in `forge_metadata.py` (see
    §ORCH-forge-orchestration-spec), a workflow driver under `ai_workflows/`, and
    a matching git script under `git_scripts/` (see
    §GIT-forge-publication).
  - Add a workflow engine by subclassing the current `WorkflowStrategy` base
    class, registering it, documenting the workflow behavior, and adding
    predefined strategy entries that select it.
  - Add or swap an editor backend by implementing `Agent` (see §AR-agent-api) and
    referencing it from predefined strategies.
  - Change post-generation recovery by editing the shared Codex-then-Pi lane in
    the workflow base class (`_run_test_with_retry`); it is built in rather than a
    per-strategy plug-in, so recovery changes apply to every workflow at once.
  - Add a prompt shape by adding a template and binding it through
    `strategies/predefined_strategies.json`.
  
  New extensions should cite the workflow or functional spec that explains why
  the behavior exists before adding architecture. Architecture declarations record
  where a behavior lives in the implementation; workflow specs record the
  operational contract; functional specs record the user-visible reason (see
  §FS-forge-issue-resolution-goal).
[recv] {"type": "message_start", "message": {"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_zmgctdKlDNEDAI0SKDdXZzvA|fc_04032c5fc02dcc81016a15ccd5316481a2825d2fdbddb66da4", "toolName": "read", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "# AR-forge-architecture: Forge architecture\n\nThis document describes the high-level implementation shape of Forge:\nwhich component owns each phase of the issue resolution defined in\n§FS-forge-issue-resolution-goal, where extensibility lives, and which\nboundaries keep generated work reviewable. The behavior Forge must satisfy is\ndefined by §FS-forge-functional-spec; this file records the implementation\nstructure chosen to satisfy it, with the workflow catalog in\n§FS-forge-workflow-spec-catalog as the behavior surface.\n\n## Architecture Map\n\n| ID | Concern |\n| --- | --- |\n| §AR-forge-architecture | overview of Forge implementation boundaries |\n| §DW-do-work-loop | worker bootstrap, self-update, stop markers, and cycle scheduling |\n| §ORCH-forge-orchestration-spec | orchestration scripts: GitHub queue claiming, worktree setup, workflow dispatch, publication handoff, and issue/project bookkeeping |\n| §GIT-forge-publication | git-scripts publication: staging, commit, PR body, labels, and issue linking |\n| §WF-forge-workflow-system | behavioral contract for the workflow layer |\n| §WF-forge-workflow-architecture | implementation split for workflow drivers, strategy configuration, workflow engines, utilities, and publication handoff |\n| §WF-forge-workflow-drivers | behavioral contract for deterministic workflow drivers |\n| §STRAT-forge-predefined-strategy-contract | behavioral contract for named strategy configuration bundles |\n| §AR-forge-control-plane | how the worker loop, dispatcher, GitHub queues, and worktrees compose |\n| §AR-forge-workflow-boundary | how workflow drivers turn a claimed issue into an isolated workflow run |\n| §AR-forge-strategy-agent-boundary | how strategy configuration, workflow engines, agents, and post-generation interventions are separated |\n| §AR-forge-verification-publication-boundary | why PR creation is a publication step after verification, not part of generation |\n| §AR-forge-extension-points | where new issue queues, strategies, agents, and PR types plug in |\n| §STRAT-workflow-strategy-registry | strategy registry and predefined strategy wiring |\n| §WF-forge-workflow-engine | workflow engines as state-machine-like run executors |\n| §WF-forge-workflow-strategy-config | predefined strategy bundles as workflow run configuration |\n\n## AR-forge-control-plane: Worker loop and dispatcher own queue control\n\nForge is shaped as a small control plane around independent workflow entry\nscripts, serving §FS-forge-issue-resolution-goal. `do-work.sh` is the stable\nshell entrypoint. It forwards arguments to `do_up_to_date_work.sh`, which keeps\nthe local Forge checkout up to date, honors stop files, applies worker limits,\nand invokes `forge_metadata.py` for one work cycle, as described in\n§DW-do-work-loop. The dispatcher owns GitHub queue scanning, issue claiming,\nworktree creation, workflow routing, review queues, project status updates, and\ncleanup; its behavior and implementation are specified in\n§ORCH-forge-orchestration-spec. PR publication is delegated to the\ngit-scripts component (§GIT-forge-publication) after the dispatcher\nobserves a PR-eligible status; the dispatched workflows themselves are defined\nseparately, in §WF-forge-workflow-system and §WF-forge-workflow-architecture.\n\nThe dispatcher routes issue work by issue labels, not by PR labels:\n\n| Issue label | Workflow driver | Successful PR label |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| `library-new-request` | `ai_workflows/add_new_library_support.py` | `library-new-request` |\n| `library-update-request` | `ai_workflows/improve_library_coverage.py` | `library-update-request` |\n| `fails-javac-compile` | `ai_workflows/fix_javac_fail.py` | `fixes-javac-fail` |\n| `fails-java-run` | `ai_workflows/fix_java_run_fail.py` | `fixes-java-run-fail` |\n| `fails-native-image-run` | `ai_workflows/fix_ni_run.py` | `fixes-native-image-run-fail` |\n\nThe control plane treats a claimed issue as exclusive work. Claiming,\nassignment checks, worktree creation, and final unassignment all belong in\n`forge_metadata.py` and the GitHub helper layer rather than in individual\nworkflow engines. Workflow drivers should receive already-resolved\ncoordinates, paths, and strategy names; they should not reimplement queue\npolicy.\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n    Wrapper[\"do-work.sh\"]\n    Worker[\"do_up_to_date_work.sh\"]\n    Dispatcher[\"forge_metadata.py\"]\n    GitHub[(\"GitHub issues / PRs / project\")]\n    Worktree[(\"isolated reachability worktree\")]\n    Entry[\"workflow driver\"]\n    PR[\"git_scripts/make_pr_*.py\"]\n\n    Wrapper --> Worker --> Dispatcher\n    Dispatcher -->|scan + claim label| GitHub\n    Dispatcher -->|create| Worktree\n    Dispatcher -->|invoke| Entry\n    Entry -->|status + metrics| Dispatcher\n    Dispatcher -->|PR-eligible status| PR\n    PR --> GitHub\n    Dispatcher -->|failure / review bookkeeping| GitHub\n```\n\n## AR-forge-workflow-boundary: Workflow drivers compose setup, workflow engine, and metrics\n\nWorkflow drivers are single-run boundaries, as defined by\n§WF-forge-workflow-drivers. They translate a claimed issue into one isolated\nrun by resolving repository\npaths, pinning the GraalVM environment, creating or checking out the feature\nbranch, preparing source context and required directories, loading the named\npredefined strategy, running the selected workflow engine, finalizing metadata,\nand writing schema-validated metrics.\n\nThe workflow driver owns run setup and finalization; the workflow engine owns\nthe state-machine-like issue-resolution process described in\n§WF-forge-workflow-architecture. The predefined strategy supplies configuration:\nwhich workflow engine, agent backend, model, prompt set, and workflow\nparameters are used for the run. This keeps every workflow aligned with the\nsame repository, metrics, and local verification contracts\n(§FS-local-ci-equivalent-verification) while letting operators select different\nservice profiles through configuration.\n\nThe reachability repository must be present as a complete checkout or worktree\nfor every generated artifact. Forge does not run Gradle-backed testing,\ndynamic-access reporting, metadata generation, or native tracing inside copied\nper-library fragments. That architecture keeps generated tests, metadata,\nGradle build logic, stats, and Forge logs in one filesystem context.\n\n## AR-forge-strategy-agent-boundary: Strategies configure workflows, agents edit code\n\nRegistered workflow implementations own the generation loop. The codebase\ncurrently names their base class `WorkflowStrategy`, but architecturally those\nclasses are workflow engines: they decide which prompt to send next, which\nGradle command to run, how to interpret output, when to reset to a checkpoint,\nand which terminal status to return. Agents own only the editing and\ncommand-execution interface exposed by `Agent`: prompts, context management,\ntoken accounting, and test-command execution.\n\nThis boundary lets a predefined strategy bind a workflow engine, agent, model,\nprompt-template set, workflow parameters, MCPs, and optional persistent\ninstructions without changing the workflow driver or the workflow implementation.\nThe workflow driver loads that bundle from `strategies/predefined_strategies.json`;\nit does not hard-code model-specific behavior.\n\nPost-generation recovery is built into the workflow base class, not a pluggable\nregistry and not selected per strategy. When the post-iteration `./gradlew test`\nstill fails during finalization, the base class runs a fixed Codex-then-Pi lane:\na Codex metadata fix first, then Pi removing the offending failing tests as a\nlast resort (see the post-generation intervention glossary in\n§FS-forge-functional-spec).\n\nDynamic-access and native-test behavior stay in workflow specs, not in this\narchitecture file. The architecture only fixes the boundaries: workflow engines\ncall shared utilities for dynamic-access reports, and native test verification\nis a reusable gate (§WF-native-test-verification-gate) that drives native\ntracing and Codex recovery through the Gradle task contract in\n§WF-native-trace-gradle-tasks. The concrete agent API and Pi adapter are\ndocumented in §AR-agent-api, and the\nstrategy bundles that bind these pieces live in the strategy registry\n(§STRAT-forge-predefined-strategy-contract, §STRAT-workflow-strategy-registry).\n\n## AR-forge-verification-publication-boundary: Git scripts publish verified work\n\nForge separates generation from publication. A workflow may edit tests,\nmetadata, index files, stats, metrics, and logs while it runs, but PR creation\nis delegated to `git_scripts/make_pr_*.py` only after the dispatcher observes a\nPR-eligible status, as required by §FS-local-ci-equivalent-verification and\n§GIT-forge-publication. The publication script\nstages the expected paths, writes a commit message with metrics context, opens\nthe pull request, applies the workflow-specific PR label, and links the result\nback to the issue.\n\nThis boundary is especially important for chunked dynamic-access work. A\nnon-final chunk publishes a reviewable PR that references the issue and carries\nthe exhaust-report state needed by the next run, as specified in\n§WF-dynamic-access-exhaust-report. The final chunk is the only one allowed to\nclose the issue. The publication layer must preserve that issue linking\ncontract instead of treating every successful chunk as a completed issue\n(§WF-chunked-dynamic-access-pr-linking).\n\nShared repository edits are allowed only when local verification proves they\nare necessary, and they must be surfaced in metrics and PR text for maintainer\nreview. Publication is therefore not a blind `git add .`; it is the point where\nworkflow-specific expected paths, labels, metrics, and human-intervention flags\nbecome visible to reviewers.\n\n## AR-forge-extension-points: New behavior plugs into one boundary at a time\n\nForge extension points are intentionally narrow:\n\n- Add an issue queue by adding a label route in `forge_metadata.py` (see\n  §ORCH-forge-orchestration-spec), a workflow driver under `ai_workflows/`, and\n  a matching git script under `git_scripts/` (see\n  §GIT-forge-publication).\n- Add a workflow engine by subclassing the current `WorkflowStrategy` base\n  class, registering it, documenting the workflow behavior, and adding\n  predefined strategy entries that select it.\n- Add or swap an editor backend by implementing `Agent` (see §AR-agent-api) and\n  referencing it from predefined strategies.\n- Change post-generation recovery by editing the shared Codex-then-Pi lane in\n  the workflow base class (`_run_test_with_retry`); it is built in rather than a\n  per-strategy plug-in, so recovery changes apply to every workflow at once.\n- Add a prompt shape by adding a template and binding it through\n  `strategies/predefined_strategies.json`.\n\nNew extensions should cite the workflow or functional spec that explains why\nthe behavior exists before adding architecture. Architecture declarations record\nwhere a behavior lives in the implementation; workflow specs record the\noperational contract; functional specs record the user-visible reason (see\n§FS-forge-issue-resolution-goal).\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1779813589505}}
